_ A substitute for a single character

IN

WHERE some_column=some_value;

LIKE - is used to search for a specified pattern in a column

IN - allows you to specify multiply values in a WHERE clauase

Joins:

INNER: Returns all rows when there is at least one match in BOTH tables SELECT

column_names(s) FROM orders a INNER JOIN customers g ON g. orders.CustomerID=a Customers.CunstomerID;

LEFT: Returns all rows from the left table, and the match rows from the right table

CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)

JavaScript

title: XML and JSON
content:
XML
  • eXtensible Markup Language
  • Designed to store and transport data
  • Both human and machine readable
  • XML stores data in plain text format. This provides a software- and hardware-independent way of storing, transporting, and sharing data.
  • XML also makes it easier to expand or upgrade to new operating systems, new applications, or new browsers, without losing data.
JSON
  • JavaScript Object Notation
  • Syntax for storing and exchanging data
  • JSON is text, written with JS object notation
  • When exchanging data between a browser and a server, the data can only be text.

title: JavaScript
content:
JavaScript
  • Used to give functionality to HTML elements
  • var means variable, used to store data
  • If a form field is empty, this function alerts a message, and returns false, to prevent the form from being submitted
  • JS can be put in the <head>, <body>, and in a separate page that can be called <script src="myScript1.js"></script>
JavaScript DOM Object
  • When a page is loaded the browser creates a Document Object Model of the page
  • With the object model, JavaScript gets all the power it needs to create dynamic HTML
  • Defines HTML elements as objects
Objects VS Arrays
  • Objects use named indexes
  • Use objects when you want element names to be strings
  • Arrays use numbered indexes
  • Use arrays when you want element names to be numbers
Common Objects
  • Strings: var carname = "Volvo XC60";
  • Math: Math.random(), Math.ceil(), Math.floor()
  • For loops, while loops, if and else if loops

title: STATS
content:
Normal distribution- Distributed around a central value w/no bias left or right. 
Spread- Standard deviation is a typical measure of the spread data. 
Standard Deviation- Is the square root of the variance. So the variance is the average of
the square differences from the Mean.  
F-Statistic- Yields a probability(p-value) that differences are due to chance.
F= (between group variability)/ (Within group variability).

content: UPDATE table_name SET column1=value1, column2=value2? WHERE some_column=some_value;var - stores data valuesDELETE FROM table_name WHERE some_column=some_value;

title: OPERATER
content: LIKE/IN & WildCardsSELECT column_names(s) FROM table_name WHERE column_name LIKE pattern/IN (value1, value2…); % = A substitute for zero or more characteristic_  = A substitute for a single character

title: JOIN
content: INNER: Returns all rows when there is at least one match in BOTH tablesSELECT column_names(s) FROM orders a INNER JOIN customers g ON g. orders.CustomerID=a Customers.CunstomerID;LEFT: Returns all rows from the left table, and the match rows from the right table

content: JSON stands for JavaScript Object Notation, a lightweight data-interchange format, "self-describing" and easy to understand JSON is language independent Since the JSON format is text only, it can easily be sent to and from a server, and used as a data format by any programming language.

title: Stats
content:
Normal distribution- Distributed around a central value w/no bias left or right. 
Spread- Standard deviation is a typical measure of the spread data. 
Standard Deviation- Is the square root of the variance. So the variance is the average of the square differences from the Mean.  
F-Statistic- Yields a probability(p-value) that differences are due to chance. F= (between group variability)/ (Within group variability). 
Interpreting Data- 1. Come up w/ a hypothesis 2. Conduct Study(Users & tasks-context, Procedure, Measures) 3. Interpret Results. (Mean, Distribution, Spread, F-statistic: basic measures)

  • Variety- Data in many forms (structured, unstructured, text, multimedia)
  • Velocity- Data in Motion (streaming data)
  • Veracity- Data in Doubt (uncertainty due to data inconsistency & incompleteness.)

title: SQL Math
content:
The SQL COUNT function returns the number of rows in a table satisfying the criteria specified in the WHERE clause. It sets the number of rows or non NULL column values.

The SQL AGGREGATE SUM() function returns the sum of all selected column.

The SQL AVG function calculates the average value of a column of numeric type. It returns the average of all non NULL values

The aggregate function SQL MAX() is used to find the maximum value or highest value of a certain column or expression. This function is useful to determine the largest of all selected values of a column.

The aggregate function SQL MIN() is used to find the minimum value or lowest value of a column or expression. This function is useful to determine the smallest of all selected values of a column.

(a)       SELECTSUM(duration) FROM activity_log WHERE log_timestamp LIKE "20170214%";

(b)       SELECTSUM(ACL.duration) AS spend_time FROM Activity_log ACL JOIN Activity AC ON

ACL.act_id = AC.act_id WHEREACL.log_timestamp LIKE "20170215%" AND AC.act_name =

"walking";

(c)       SELECTSUM(ACL.duration) AS spend_time FROM Activity_log ACL JOIN Activity AC ON

ACL.act_id = AC.act_id WHEREACL.log_timestamp < "20170215120000" AND

ACL.log_timestamp >= "20170215000000" ANDAC.act_name = 'walking'

(d)       SELECTCOUNT( DISTINCT act_id ) AS total_count FROM Activity_log;

(e)       SELECTSUM(AC.act_cal) AS calories_consumption, SUBSTR(ACL.log_timestamp, 1, 8) ASdate FROM Activity AC JOIN Activity_log ACL ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id GROUP BYdate;

(f)       SELECT AC.act_name FROM Activity_log ACL JOINActivity AC ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id

WHERE ACL.log_timestampLIKE "20170215%" ORDER BY AC.act_cal DESC LIMIT 0,1;

title: GTTK1
content:
Stats:
Normal distribution- Distributed around a central value w/no bias left or right. 
Spread- Standard deviation is a typical measure of the spread data. 
Standard Deviation- Is the square root of the variance. So the variance is the average of the square differences from the Mean.  
F-Statistic- Yields a probability(p-value) that differences are due to chance. F= (between group variability)/ (Within group variability). 
Interpreting Data- 1. Come up w/ a hypothesis 2. Conduct Study(Users & tasks-context, Procedure, Measures) 3. Interpret Results. (Mean, Distribution, Spread, F-statistic: basic measures) 
Data Analysis:
Descriptive-Describes behaviors and changes (overall or individual)
  • Periodicities
  • Spikes
  • Shifts
*Question: What is happening?
Relational- How are things that are happening related to each other?
Causal- What factors cause what is happening?
Information Model- Entity: People or objects, Location: Spatial or Conceptual, Event: Occurrences or discovered facts
V's
Velocity, Variety, Volume, (Veracity, Value)
  • Volume- Data at Rest (Terabytes to exabytes of existing data to process) 
  • Variety- Data in many forms (structured, unstructured, text, multimedia)
  • Velocity- Data in Motion (streaming data)
  • Veracity- Data in Doubt (uncertainty due to data inconsistency & incompleteness.)

title: GTTK 2
content:
Client vs. Server
client: 
  • browser
  • codes are visible
  • doesn't require server to create data
Server: 
  • codes are invisible in page source
  • provide data to display on  browser,
  • not reside on browse
Languages and Data Formats
HTML (HyperText Markup Language)
  • formatting/building language for the web
  • denotes document structure
  • HTML5 includes new tags: semantic elements (header, footer, etc), attributes (date, time), graphic elements (svg, canvas), and multimedia (video, audio) 
CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)
  • stylize HTML documents
  • concise, specific notation of display/layout
JavaScript
  • add dynamic actions, interactivity to webpage
  • scripting language, interpreted and executed without compilation
  • executed while page loads
XML
  • like HTML, but without predefined tags
  • universal markup language for data exchange
  • tags & values, tree structure
  • separate content from appearance
JSON
  • alternative to XML, subset of JavaScript
  • lightweight, language independent data format

title: 3 V's of Big Data
content:
Volume: Amount processed 
Velocity: static vs live stream
Variety: types, structure
(Value, Veracity)

HTML- Hyper Text Markup language, the mark up formatting language for the web

                Language to build web pages (document structure, content presentation). html

HTML5 - similar but the latest version of hypertext Makeup language

XML ? extensible markup language, looks like HTML with no predefined tags, to store and to transfer data, XML tags are case sensitive and element must be properly nested

JSON(JavaScript Object Notation) ? alternate to XML, a subset of JavaScript programming language lightweight computer data interchangeable format and is language independent data format 

Why do we need it?  Information exchange: separate content from appearance, to store and transfer data, distributing data over the internet

JavaScript: scripting language, nothing to do with Java, to interpreted language, scripts are executed without compilation, usually embedded in HTML and add interactivity to HTML pages

Roles: HTML is to define the content of web pages

                CSS to specify the layout of the web pages

                JavaScript to program the behavior of the web pages

supposed to be easier that everybody can write it

URI/URL: Uniform resource Identifier
An "address" that is unique & used to identify each
 resource on the web. 
HTTP: Hypertext transfer protocols 
Allows for the retrieval of linked resources from the web.  
CSS: Cascading Style Sheets
Used to specify the layout of a web page.

title: link
Defenitions
content:
Client vs. Server
Client: 
  • browser
  • codes are visible
  • doesn't require server to create data
Server: 
  • codes are invisible in page source
  • provide data to display on  browser,
  • not reside on browse
Languages and Data Formats
HTML (HyperText Markup Language)
  • formatting/building language for the web
  • denotes document structure
  • HTML5 includes new tags: semantic elements (header, footer, etc), attributes (date, time), graphic elements (svg, canvas), and multimedia (video, audio) 
CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)
  • stylize HTML documents
  • concise, specific notation of display/layout
JavaScript
  • add dynamic actions, interactivity to webpage
  • scripting language, interpreted and executed without compilation
  • executed while page loads
XML
  • like HTML, but without predefined tags
  • universal markup language for data exchange
  • tags & values, tree structure
  • separate content from appearance
JSON
  • alternative to XML, subset of JavaScript
  • lightweight, language independent data format

title: Data Analysis
content:
Normal distribution- Distributed around a central value w/no bias left or right. 
Spread- Standard deviation is a typical measure of the spread data. 
Standard Deviation- Is the square root of the variance. So the variance is the average of the square differences from the Mean.  
F-Statistic- Yields a probability(p-value) that differences are due to chance. F= (between group variability)/ (Within group variability). 
Interpreting Data- 1. Come up w/ a hypothesis 2. Conduct Study(Users & tasks-context, Procedure, Measures) 3. Interpret Results. (Mean, Distribution, Spread, F-statistic: basic measures)

title: JOIN Properties
content:
Inner Join: returns all rows with at least one match in both tables
Left Join: returns all rows from left table and matched rows from right table
Right Join: returns all rows from right table and matched rows from left table
Full Join: returns all rows when there is a match in one of the tables

The SQL COUNT function returns the number of rows in a table satisfying the criteria specified in the WHERE clause. It sets the number of rows or non NULL column values.

The SQL AGGREGATE SUM() function returns the sum of all selected column.

The SQL AVG function calculates the average value of a column of numeric type. It returns the average of all non NULL values

The aggregate function SQL MAX() is used to find the maximum value or highest value of a certain column or expression. This function is useful to determine the largest of all selected values of a column.

The aggregate function SQL MIN() is used to find the minimum value or lowest value of a column or expression. This function is useful to determine the smallest of all selected values of a column.

title: HTML
content:
HTML- Hyper Text Markup language, the mark up formatting language for the web

                Language to build web pages (document structure, content presentation). html

HTML5 - similar but the latest version of hypertext Makeup language

XML ? extensible markup language, looks like HTML with no predefined tags, to store and to transfer data, XML tags are case sensitive and element must be properly nested

JSON(JavaScript Object Notation) ? alternate to XML, a subset of JavaScript programming language lightweight computer data interchangeable format and is language independent data format 

Why do we need it?  Information exchange: separate content from appearance, to store and transfer data, distributing data over the internet

JavaScript: scripting language, nothing to do with Java, to interpreted language, scripts are executed without compilation, usually embedded in HTML and add interactivity to HTML pages

Roles: HTML is to define the content of web pages

                CSS to specify the layout of the web pages

                JavaScript to program the behavior of the web pages

supposed to be easier that everybody can write it

URI/URL: Uniform resource Identifier
An "address" that is unique & used to identify each
 resource on the web. 
HTTP: Hypertext transfer protocols 
Allows for the retrieval of linked resources from the web.  
CSS: Cascading Style Sheets
Used to specify the layout of a web page.

title: SQL definitions
content:
• NOT NULL - Indicates that a column cannot store NULL value

  • UNIQUE - Ensures that each row for a column must have a unique value

  • PRIMARY KEY - A combination of a NOT NULL and UNIQUE. Ensures that a column (or combination of two or more columns) have a unique identity which helps to find a particular record in a table more easily and quickly

  • FOREIGN KEY - Ensure the referential integrity of the data in one table to match values in another table

SELECT SUM(duration)
AS TOTAL_TIME
FROM Activity_log
WHERE log_timestamp
LIKE "20170214%";

SELECT SUM(duration)
AS "Walking Time"
FROM Activity_log
WHERE ((log_timestamp
LIKE "201702150%")
OR (log_timestamp LIKE "2017021510%")
OR (log_timestamp LIKE "2017021511%"))
AND (act_id = 1);

SELECT Activity.act_name, (Activity_log.duration/60) * Activity.act_cal AS "Calorie Count", Activity_log.log_timestamp
FROM Activity
INNER JOIN Activity_log
ON Activity.act_id=Activity_log.act_id;

title: Group By, HAVING
content:
GROUP BY statement is used with an aggregate function (like: count, max, min, sum)

SELECT column_name, aggregate_function(column_name)
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name operator value
GROUP BY column_name;

HAVING:Was added to SQL bc the WHERE keyword could not be used with aggregate functions

SELECT Employees.LastName, COUNT(Orders.OrderID) AS NumberOfOrders FROM (Orders
INNER JOIN Employees
ON Orders.EmployeeID=Employees.EmployeeID)
GROUP BY LastName
HAVING COUNT(Orders.OrderID) > 10;

JOIN
INNER: Returns all rows when there is at least one match in BOTH tables SELECT column_names(s) FROM orders a INNER JOIN customers g ON g. orders.CustomerID=a Customers.CunstomerID; 
LEFT: Returns all rows from the left table, and the match rows from the right table.
Right Join: returns all rows from right table and matched rows from left table
Order by- sorts the results by ascending or descending

CREATE TABLE `Activity` (act_id int(11) NOT NULLact_id int(11) NOT NULLact_cal int(11) NOT NULLPRIMARY KEY (`act_id`),UNIQUE KEY `act_id` (`act_id`)  );INSERT INTO `Activity` (`act_id`, `act_name`, `act_cal`) VALUES(1, 'walking', 60),(2, 'jogging', 250),(3, 'meditating', 5),(4, 'rowing', 420),(5, 'fencing', 310),(6, 'tennis', 560),(7, 'yoga', 180),(8, 'showering', 60);2.               CREATE TABLE  `Activity_log` (`log_id` int(11) NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,`act_id` int(11) NOT NULL,`duration` int(11) NOT NULL,`log_timestamp` varchar(14) NOT NULL,PRIMARY KEY (`log_id`),UNIQUE KEY `log_id` (`log_id`)     );INSERT INTO `Activity_log` (`log_id`, `act_id`, `duration`, `log_timestamp`) VALUES(1, 1, 60, '20170214085000'),(2, 2, 25, '20170214095100'),(3, 3, 5, '20170214101100'),(4, 6, 90, '20170215070000'),(5, 1, 30, '20170215084000'),(6, 8, 20, '20170215101000'),(7, 1, 20, '20170215111000'),(8, 1, 20, '20170215121000'),(9, 3, 30, '20170215141000'),(10, 1, 20, '20170215151000'),(11, 1, 10, '20170215153500'),(12, 8, 20, '20170215170000');3. (a) how many minutes were you active on 2017/02/14?SELECT SUM(duration) FROM activity_log WHERE log_timestamp LIKE "20170214%";(b) how many minutes did you spend on walking 2017/02/5?SELECT SUM(ACL.duration) AS spend_time FROM Activity_log ACL JOIN Activity AC ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id WHERE ACL.log_timestamp LIKE "20170215%" AND AC.act_name = "walking"; (c) how many minutes did you spend on walking 2017/02/15 before noon?SELECT SUM(ACL.duration) AS spend_time FROM Activity_log ACL JOIN Activity AC ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id WHERE ACL.log_timestamp < "20170215120000" AND ACL.log_timestamp >= "20170215000000" AND AC.act_name = 'walking' (d) how many different kinds of activities did you do? SELECT COUNT( DISTINCT act_id ) AS total_count FROM Activity_log; (e) how many calories consumption each day?SELECT SUM(AC.act_cal) AS calories_consumption, SUBSTR(ACL.log_timestamp, 1, 8) AS date FROM Activity AC JOIN Activity_log ACL ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id GROUP BY date;(f) what is the most exhausting activity that you did on 2017/02/15?SELECT AC.act_name FROM Activity_log ACL JOIN Activity AC ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id WHERE ACL.log_timestamp LIKE "20170215%" ORDER BY AC.act_cal DESC LIMIT 0,1;4.Why do we use two tables here instead of one? (Why don?t we just log behaviors explicitly with activity name and calories?)Ans: . To use two tables here is the result of database normalization. The purpose is to maintain table integrity, reduce dependency, and avoid redundant actions.

title: Arrays vs objects
content:
Arrays use numbers to access its "elements". In this example, person[0] returns John:

Objects use names to access its "members". In this example, person.firstName returns John:

In JavaScript, arrays use numbered indexes.  

In JavaScript, objects use named indexes.


Array: var person = ["John", "Doe", 46]; 

Object: var person = {firstName:"John", lastName:"Doe", age:46};

title: What is JavaScript?
content: It is a “scripting” language, nothing to do with Java (java is all purpose lang).It is interpreted language, scripts are executed without compilation.Usually embedded in HTML pages & add interactivity to HTML pages.It will be executed immediately while the page loads into your browser. (sometimes, it is not what we want; we may want to execute when user trigger it or when the page loads)JavaScript is case sensitive. (same as Java)

var Result;

var yourInput = "placeholder";

var computerGen;

var count = 0;

var Win = 0;

var Lose = 0;

var Tie = 0;

var Rock = 0;

var Paper = 0;

var Scissors = 0;


document.getElementById("Tally").innerHTML = count;


function getName() {

  var nam3 = prompt("What Is Your Name?");

  document.getElementById("nombre").innerHTML = nam3;

}


var compare = function(choice1, choice2) {

  if (choice1 === choice2) {

    Result = "Tie!";

    Tie++;

  }

  if (choice1 === "rock") {

    if (choice2 === "scissors") {

      Result = "Win";

      Win++;

    } else {

      if (choice2 === "paper") {

        Result = "Lose";

        Lose++;

      }

    }

  }

  if (choice1 === "paper") {

    if (choice2 === "rock") {

      Result = "Win";

      Win++;

    } else {

      if (choice2 === "scissors") {

        Result = "Lose";

        Lose++;

      }

    }

  }

  if (choice1 === "scissors") {

    if (choice2 === "rock") {

      Result = "Lose";

      Lose++;

    } else {

      if (choice2 === "paper") {

        Result = "Win";

        Win++;

      }

    }

  }

};


var getCheckedRadio = function() {

  var radioButtons = document.getElementsByName("yourC");

  for (var x = 0; x < radioButtons.length; x++) {

    if (radioButtons[x].checked) {

      yourInput = radioButtons[x].value;

    }

  }

};


function playplay() {

  computerGen = Math.random();

  getCheckedRadio();

  if (computerGen < 0.34) {

    computerGen = "rock";

Rock++;

  } else if (computerGen <= 0.67) {

    computerGen = "paper";

Paper++;

  } else {

    computerGen = "scissors";

Scissors++;

  }

  document.getElementById("CC").innerHTML = computerGen;

  compare(yourInput, computerGen);

  document.getElementById("RES").innerHTML = Result;

  count++;

  document.getElementById("Tally").innerHTML = count + " time(s)!";

  document.getElementById("Wi").innerHTML = Win;

  document.getElementById("Lo").innerHTML = Lose;

  document.getElementById("Ti").innerHTML = Tie;

  

  document.getElementById("rr").innerHTML = Rock;

  document.getElementById("pp").innerHTML = Paper;

  document.getElementById("ss").innerHTML = Scissors;

}

(a) how many minutes were you active on 2017/02/14?SELECT SUM(duration) FROM activity_log WHERE log_timestamp LIKE "20170214%";(b) how many minutes did you spend on walking 2017/02/5?SELECT SUM(ACL.duration) AS spend_time FROM Activity_log ACL JOIN Activity AC ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id WHERE ACL.log_timestamp LIKE "20170215%" AND AC.act_name = "walking"; (c) how many minutes did you spend on walking 2017/02/15 before noon?SELECT SUM(ACL.duration) AS spend_time FROM Activity_log ACL JOIN Activity AC ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id WHERE ACL.log_timestamp < "20170215120000" AND ACL.log_timestamp >= "20170215000000" AND AC.act_name = 'walking' (d) how many different kinds of activities did you do? SELECT COUNT( DISTINCT act_id ) AS total_count FROM Activity_log; (e) how many calories consumption each day?SELECT SUM(AC.act_cal) AS calories_consumption, SUBSTR(ACL.log_timestamp, 1, 8) AS date FROM Activity AC JOIN Activity_log ACL ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id GROUP BY date;(f) what is the most exhausting activity that you did on 2017/02/15?SELECT AC.act_name FROM Activity_log ACL JOIN Activity AC ON ACL.act_id = AC.act_id WHERE ACL.log_timestamp LIKE "20170215%" ORDER BY AC.act_cal DESC LIMIT 0,1;

title: SQL
content:
Select 
  • SELECT * FROM Customers; select all
  • SELECT column1, column2, ...
    FROM table_name; specific columns
  • SELECT DISTINCT City FROM Customers; Selects distinct values, no repeats
Where
  • SELECT column1, column2, ...
    FROM table_name
    WHERE condition;
  • Operators include: =, !=, >, <, >=, <=, BETWEEN, LIKE, IN
Like
  • 'a%' starts with a
  • '%a' ends with a
  • '_r%' r in second position

title: Data Analytics
content:
Descriptive-Describes behaviors and changes (overall or individual) (Periodicities, Spikes,Shifts)
*Question: What is happening?
Relational- How are things that are happening related to each other?
Causal- What factors cause what is happening?

Guidlines for Surveys: 1)Get Specific 2)Avoid 1)Ambiguious? 2)Double-Barreled ?
3)Negative Words 4)Bias  *Better to reuse then reinvent
Organizing Survey:1)include instructions 2)Group ?s into sections with similar topic/ideas
3)Leave for end 1)sensitive qs 2)demographic qs   4)consider length in design.
Experiment vs Survey: A user experiment systematically tests how different system aspects (manipulations) influence the users? experience and behavior (observations).
A survey systematically tests how certain aspects of the user (observations) influence the users? experience and behavior (observations)

Control Experiment: In a controlled experiment you compare two or more alternatives to determine how they affect outcomes of interest. Test 1 or more hypothesis. To test Hypoth, change indep to see effect on depend. Depend:Outcome or effect  Indep:input or cause
Ind variables: 1)dif types of tech or devices 2)dif types of design 3)user characteristics 4)context of use
Components and Procedure:1)choose treat/conditions 2)Random assign units to condition 
3)Apply treat and measures 4)Analyze results
Remember to appropriately introduce the study, give necessary instruction, & debrief after.

Between: each user member of only 1 condition. Use for user experience. Closer to real world usage situation. No unwanted carry over effects.
Half a half b: Realistic interaction. Manipulation hidden. Many participants needed.
Within:User experience multiple conditions. Use for psychological research. effects typically smaller. Nice to control between-subjects variability.
A first then B: Remove subject variability. Part may see thru manip.Spill-over effect
A and B same time: Remove subject variability. Participants can compare condition. Not real interacti.FIELD STUDY: 1) can be more quantitative 2) More subjects so can be more generalizable 3)Less in depth 4)less supervised

Prototype: A prototype is an early sample, model, or release of a product built to test a concept or process or to act as a thing to be replicated or learned from. Prototyping serves to provide specifications for a real, working system rather than a theoretical one. 
Paper Prototype: 1)Fixed components (the window frame) 2)variable components(major components that occur regularly, screens, menus, dialog boxes. 3)Dynamic Components: things based entirely on individual interaction (gen on fly)
